The paper discusses the design of an algorithm for performing Genome-Wide Association Studies (GWAS) on multi-core architectures, which involves solving a sequence of correlated generalized least-squares problems. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. Additionally, the paper deals with the challenge of computing petaflops over terabytes of data, which could place it in the Numerical Analysis (cs.NA) sub-category. The use of GWAS in computational biology also suggests that the paper could belong to the Databases (cs.DB) sub-category. The paper also discusses the decomposition of computation into tasks to be distributed among available cores, which could place it in the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Finally, the paper provides guidelines for developing and optimizing numerical algorithms, which could place it in the Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science (cs.CE) sub-category.
